-- allium: 3
-- turbo_kv_residual_window.allium

-- Scope: residual-window KV-cache overlay — maintain a separate
-- fp16/bf16 ring-buffer copy of the K vector for the most recent
-- N positions, alongside the core quantised K cache. Every token
-- is still quantised into the main cache; the overlay exists
-- in parallel.
--
-- Composes on top of turbo-kv-4b.allium and turbo-kv-3b.allium
-- (and any other lossy K-cache scheme). The overlay writes do
-- not affect the main cache's contents or correctness in any
-- way — they are a second storage path maintained for a future
-- attention read path that can consult them for recent tokens.
--
-- Citable sources:
--
--   [PAPER]       Zandieh et al., arxiv 2504.19874. Paper does
--                 not model a residual window — it treats the full
--                 sequence as a single quantisation batch.
--
--   [TONBI-V3]    tonbistudio/turboquant-pytorch compressors_v3.py.
--                 Introduces residual_window as a core V3 concept.
--                 Measured evidence (README needle-in-haystack on
--                 Llama 3.2):
--                   K4/V4 rw=128:  EXACT at 2K and 4K ctx
--                   K4/V4 rw=0:    MISS (garbage output)
--                   K4/V2 rw=0:    MISS
--                 The rw=0 MISS result is the critical evidence:
--                 symmetric 4-bit K quantisation without a residual
--                 window fails the most basic retrieval task.
--                 README: "What doesn't work: 3-4 bit compression
--                 without a residual window produces garbage, same
--                 as V2."
--
--   [QUANT.CPP]   Does NOT implement a residual window. Our
--                 llama.cpp port addresses this gap.
--
-- Difference from [TONBI-V3] framing: [TONBI-V3] is an eviction
-- model — recent tokens are held in fp16 and quantised on eviction
-- past the window. This spec is an *overlay* model — every token
-- is quantised into the main cache as usual, and a separate
-- fp16/bf16 ring buffer additionally holds the last N K vectors
-- per stream per layer. The overlay is redundant storage, not
-- the authoritative copy.
--
-- The overlay is read by the attention path via a two-pass
-- flash-attention with an online-softmax merge: Pass B reads
-- the position-ordered overlay slice for the last
-- residual_window positions; Pass A reads the main quantised
-- cache for older positions; the two are merged at query
-- granularity. Pass B requires the overlay to hold post-RoPE
-- K, which constrains every cache type that wants to feed the
-- overlay to store post-RoPE K (turbo_kv_4b included).
--
-- Still aspirational and flagged below: rewind handling on
-- SequencePositionsRemoved (concrete callers include MTP
-- draft rejection and prompt rewind), Vulkan port of the
-- overlay write + read, and overlay persistence across
-- session save/load.

-- ============================================================
-- External Entities
-- ============================================================

-- One K vector produced for a single (layer, stream, position)
-- by the forward pass. The overlay mirrors this value at the
-- ring-buffer slot for the position.
external entity KVector {
    data: Set<Decimal>
    count: Integer
    layer: Integer
    stream: Integer
    position: Integer
}

-- The context in which the cache lives. Used to bound the
-- residual window against sequence length.
external entity Context {
    n_ctx: Integer
    n_layer: Integer
    n_stream: Integer
}

-- ============================================================
-- Enumerations
-- ============================================================

-- Runtime overlay storage dtype. The CLI may accept an "auto"
-- sentinel, but that is resolved into one of these two values
-- before the overlay is allocated. See ResolveOverlayDtypeAuto.
enum OverlayDtype { f16 | bf16 }

-- ============================================================
-- Config
-- ============================================================

config {
    -- Size of the ring-buffer overlay, in tokens. [TONBI-V3]
    -- default is 128. 0 disables the overlay entirely (no
    -- allocation, no writes, no reads). Measured needle-in-
    -- haystack evidence in [TONBI-V3] puts 128 at the knee for
    -- 4-bit K at the 3B-parameter scale on Llama 3.2.
    residual_window: Integer = 128

    -- Runtime overlay dtype. Concrete values only; the "auto"
    -- CLI sentinel is resolved by ResolveOverlayDtypeAuto before
    -- reaching this parameter.
    overlay_dtype: OverlayDtype = f16
}

-- ============================================================
-- Rules
-- ============================================================

-- Compute the ring-buffer slot for a (stream, position) pair.
-- Load-bearing for downstream reasoning about overwrites,
-- rollback and the overlay read path. The overlay tensor is
-- laid out as [n_embd_k_gqa, residual_window, n_stream]; the
-- flat slot index is stream * residual_window + (position mod
-- residual_window). The modulo is a black-box function since
-- the Allium expression language does not include %.
rule ComputeOverlaySlot {
    when: OverlaySlotRequested(stream, position)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0

    let slot = stream * config.residual_window + modulo(position, config.residual_window)

    ensures: OverlaySlotResolved(
        stream: stream,
        position: position,
        slot: slot
    )
}

-- On each decoded token, the K vector for that token is written
-- into the overlay at the ring-buffer slot for (stream, position).
-- This runs in parallel with the main cache's own append; it does
-- not displace, gate, or depend on the main-cache write.
--
-- Writes overwrite any stale data at the same slot (ring wrap);
-- at position p the slot (p mod residual_window) for that stream
-- last held data from position (p - residual_window).
rule AppendOverlayRow {
    when: KVectorProduced(k)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0
    requires: k.count > 0

    ensures: OverlaySlotResolved(
        stream: k.stream,
        position: k.position,
        slot: k.stream * config.residual_window + modulo(k.position, config.residual_window)
    )

    ensures: OverlayWriteCommitted(
        layer: k.layer,
        stream: k.stream,
        position: k.position,
        data: k.data
    )

    @guidance
        -- Implementation: the graph-build path calls
        -- cpy_k_window(k_cur, k_window_idxs, il) alongside
        -- cpy_k for the main cache. The dtype of the stored
        -- bytes matches config.overlay_dtype after resolution.
}

-- The five rules below capture the OverlayConsistentAfterMutation
-- obligation across the sequence-mutating operations that re-bind
-- positions to cells. AppendOverlayRow writes are correct as long
-- as the (cell, position) binding from the most recent write is
-- still in effect; any operation that breaks that binding requires
-- the overlay to be reconciled before the next read.
--
-- Common hazard: a single ring slot is written by multiple
-- positions of the form p mod residual_window == slot. The most
-- recent write displaces earlier ones. When a mutation removes
-- the most-recent writer's position from the cache, redirects it
-- to a different cell, or copies it without updating the
-- destination's overlay, the slot's bytes no longer correspond
-- to the position currently expected at that slot — silently
-- incorrect attention for surviving positions whose slot collides.
--
-- Strategy selection is shared across all five rules and is
-- recorded as an open question (RECONCILIATION STRATEGIES below
-- on ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceRemoval).
--
-- Concrete callers driving each rule:
--   ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceRemoval — MTP draft rejection,
--     prompt rewind, kv-cache compaction.
--   ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceShift — context-window slide once
--     n_ctx is exhausted (positions shift left); prompt-prefix
--     trim with re-positioning.
--   ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceDivide — sliding-window scaled
--     compaction; some sequence-merge schemes.
--   ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceCopy — beam search clone; speculative
--     decode forking; multi-sequence prompt sharing.
--   ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceKeep — single-sequence retention
--     after multi-sequence eval; eviction of all but one.

-- Reverse of AppendOverlayRow for sequence-position removal.
-- After SequencePositionsRemoved(stream, p_min, p_max), cells
-- in [p_min, p_max] have been removed from `stream`'s view of
-- the cache. Overlay slots last written by those positions
-- still hold their bytes. The reconciliation obligation: no
-- subsequent read returns K from a removed position.
rule ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceRemoval {
    when: SequencePositionsRemoved(stream, p_min, p_max)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0
    requires: p_min <= p_max

    ensures: OverlayConsistentAfterMutation(stream: stream)

    @guidance
        -- RECONCILIATION STRATEGIES (shared across all five
        -- ReconcileOverlay* rules; each correct, with different
        -- cost profiles):
        --
        --   (A) RESTORE FROM MAIN: for each ring slot whose
        --       last-effective writer position is no longer
        --       bound to the post-mutation cache, look up the
        --       most recent SURVIVING position whose
        --       pos mod residual_window == slot (in the
        --       post-mutation cache), dequant its K from main,
        --       requantise (if overlay dtype differs) and
        --       store into the slot. Cheap when the affected
        --       set is small (e.g. typical MTP draft rejection
        --       k≤8). Cost: dequant + write per affected slot.
        --
        --   (B) PER-SLOT VALIDITY: maintain a parallel "slot
        --       fresh" bitmap. Reconciliation clears bits for
        --       affected slots; AppendOverlayRow sets them on
        --       write; the read path falls back to main-cache
        --       K (Pass A's boundary-cut path) for slots whose
        --       bit is clear. Cost: bitmap maintenance, more
        --       complex Pass B mask construction.
        --
        --   (C) FULL REBUILD: clear the entire affected stream's
        --       overlay; the next residual_window decodes refill
        --       it. The attention read path must tolerate a
        --       partial overlay (mask unfilled slots) until
        --       refill. Cost: degraded attention quality during
        --       refill.
        --
        --   (D) RESTRICT: forbid the mutation from reaching the
        --       recent window (caller error if affected positions
        --       overlap [seq_len - residual_window, seq_len]).
        --       Cost: limits caller behaviour (e.g. caps MTP
        --       draft batch size, restricts context-shift reach).
}

-- After SequencePositionsShifted(stream, p_min, p_max, delta),
-- cells in [p_min, p_max] now hold position old_pos + delta;
-- their K data is unchanged at the cell level. The overlay's
-- slot↔position mapping (slot = pos mod residual_window) is
-- stale because the slot used by old_pos is generally not the
-- slot for old_pos + delta. The reconciliation obligation:
-- subsequent reads return correct K for the post-shift positions.
rule ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceShift {
    when: SequencePositionsShifted(stream, p_min, p_max, delta)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0
    requires: p_min <= p_max

    ensures: OverlayConsistentAfterMutation(stream: stream)

    @guidance
        -- See ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceRemoval for strategies.
        -- Shift-specific note: strategy (A) requires moving K
        -- bytes between slots (slot for old_pos → slot for
        -- old_pos + delta) for every shifted cell whose new
        -- position falls in the post-shift recent window. When
        -- |delta| is a multiple of residual_window, the slot
        -- mapping is preserved and no overlay work is needed
        -- (rare in practice).
}

-- After SequencePositionsDivided(stream, p_min, p_max, divisor),
-- cells in [p_min, p_max] now hold position old_pos / divisor.
-- Multiple cells may collapse to the same target position
-- (lossy compression of the position axis). Same staleness as
-- shift, plus possible position collisions.
rule ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceDivide {
    when: SequencePositionsDivided(stream, p_min, p_max, divisor)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0
    requires: p_min <= p_max
    requires: divisor > 0

    ensures: OverlayConsistentAfterMutation(stream: stream)

    @guidance
        -- See ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceRemoval for strategies.
        -- Divide-specific note: position collisions mean the
        -- post-mutation cache may have fewer distinct positions
        -- than before; slot occupancy may be sparser than the
        -- pre-mutation overlay suggests. Strategy (A) needs to
        -- pick a tie-breaker (e.g. last writer wins, or the
        -- main cache's effective head wins). Strategy (C) full
        -- rebuild side-steps the tie-breaker question.
}

-- After SequenceCopied(src_stream, dst_stream, p_min, p_max),
-- cells in [p_min, p_max] of src_stream are now also bound to
-- dst_stream at the same positions. dst_stream's overlay has
-- not seen any AppendOverlayRow for those positions; reads
-- against dst_stream's overlay would return whatever bytes
-- the slots happen to hold (initial zero or previous wrap).
rule ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceCopy {
    when: SequenceCopied(src_stream, dst_stream, p_min, p_max)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0
    requires: p_min <= p_max

    ensures: OverlayConsistentAfterMutation(stream: dst_stream)

    @guidance
        -- See ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceRemoval for strategies.
        -- Copy-specific note: strategy (A) becomes "copy the
        -- corresponding overlay slots from src_stream's overlay
        -- to dst_stream's overlay" — cheaper than re-quantising
        -- from main, since both overlays share the same dtype
        -- and the source slots are already correct. Strategy
        -- (B) per-slot validity must propagate the bitmap too.
}

-- After SequenceKept(seq_id), all sequences except seq_id are
-- removed. Streams other than the kept seq_id's stream lose
-- all their cells. Their overlay slots remain populated with
-- K from removed cells, which would corrupt subsequent reads
-- if those streams are later re-used.
rule ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceKeep {
    when: SequenceKept(seq_id)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0

    ensures: OverlayConsistentAfterKeep(kept_seq_id: seq_id)

    @guidance
        -- See ReconcileOverlayOnSequenceRemoval for strategies.
        -- Keep-specific notes: the kept seq_id's stream is
        -- unchanged; every other stream needs reconciliation
        -- because all its positions are now removed. Strategy
        -- (C) full rebuild is the natural fit for the dropped
        -- streams since "all positions removed" leaves nothing
        -- to restore from. The single OverlayConsistentAfterKeep
        -- ensure covers the obligation for all streams jointly;
        -- splitting per-dropped-stream emits would require
        -- modelling a Streams collection in this spec, which
        -- is currently abstracted away.
}

-- Auto-resolution of config.overlay_dtype when the CLI passes
-- the "auto" sentinel: inspect the model's native K projection
-- float type and pick BF16 if any model weights are BF16, F16
-- if all float weights are F16 or F32, and BF16 as a safe
-- upgrade when weights are quantised with no F16 fallback.
-- Fires once at context initialisation before any overlay
-- allocation occurs.
rule ResolveOverlayDtypeAuto {
    when: OverlayDtypeAutoRequested(context, model_has_bf16_weights, model_has_only_float_weights)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0

    ensures:
        if model_has_bf16_weights:
            OverlayDtypeResolved(context: context, dtype: bf16)
        else if model_has_only_float_weights:
            OverlayDtypeResolved(context: context, dtype: f16)
        else:
            OverlayDtypeResolved(context: context, dtype: bf16)

    @guidance
        -- The sentinel handling is a CLI concern; this rule
        -- describes the observable resolution that tests can
        -- verify. See open question on whether the rule belongs
        -- in config defaults instead.
}

-- Attention-read rule: reconcile the main (quantised) cache
-- with the overlay for the most recent residual_window positions.
-- At query time, for each attended position in the last
-- residual_window of the sequence, the attention read serves K
-- from the overlay (lossless, fp16/bf16). Positions older than
-- residual_window are served from the main cache only.
rule ReadKVRecentFromOverlay {
    when: ReadKVForAttention(query_position, attended_position, stream, seq_len)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0
    requires: attended_position > seq_len - config.residual_window
    requires: attended_position <= seq_len

    ensures: AttentionKeySource(
        query_position: query_position,
        attended_position: attended_position,
        source: overlay
    )

    @guidance
        -- Implementation direction: two-pass flash-attention
        -- with online-softmax merge.
        --   Pass A: FA over positions in [0, seq_len -
        --     residual_window), K = main quantised cache, V = V
        --     cache. Existing turbo_kv_4b FA kernel handles this
        --     verbatim; no kernel change.
        --   Pass B: FA over positions in [seq_len -
        --     residual_window, seq_len), K = overlay reshaped
        --     view, V = V cache. Existing fp16/bf16 FA kernel
        --     handles this verbatim given correct K shape.
        --   Merge: online-softmax combine using (M, S) per query
        --     per head from each pass: M_new = max(M_a, M_b);
        --     scale_a = exp(M_a - M_new); scale_b = exp(M_b -
        --     M_new); S_new = scale_a*S_a + scale_b*S_b;
        --     VKQ_new = (scale_a*VKQ_a + scale_b*VKQ_b); final
        --     output = VKQ_new / S_new.
        -- Rejected: single-pass assembled-K — would require
        -- dequantising the whole main cache to fp16/bf16 every
        -- decode (5+ GFLOP and 500+ MB scratch at 35B-A3B /
        -- 32K ctx), defeating the compression.
        -- Prerequisites: extend ggml_flash_attn_ext to emit
        -- per-query (M, S, VKQ_unscaled) — the existing CPU
        -- kernel already computes these internally as
        -- chunk-partial state for its threaded reduction
        -- (see ops.cpp around the partials write in
        -- flash_attn_ext_f16_one_chunk). Expose via a new
        -- ggml_flash_attn_ext_lse API that outputs shape
        -- [DV+2, n_head, n_tokens] with the extra rows holding
        -- M and S. Merge implementable with existing ggml ops
        -- once LSE is exposed (no new merge op required).
        --
        -- RoPE state alignment: Pass B's K must arrive at the
        -- attention kernel in the same RoPE state as Q.
        -- AppendOverlayRow's storage policy mirrors cpy_k
        -- verbatim, so the overlay inherits the main cache's
        -- RoPE state per cache type:
        --   - post-RoPE store (f16, bf16, and turbo_kv_4b): the
        --     overlay holds post-RoPE K; Pass B reads the
        --     position-ordered slice directly with no extra RoPE
        --     step. This is the supported and tested two-pass
        --     configuration.
        --   - pre-RoPE store (split-K caches, where cpy_k stores
        --     pre-RoPE K and the main-cache read path applies
        --     on-the-fly RoPE): two-pass dispatch falls back to
        --     single-pass FA. A correct two-pass + LSE merge
        --     for pre-RoPE storage requires the rope-on-the-fly
        --     output to compose with the merge in a way that
        --     has not been achieved — the apparent symbolic
        --     equivalence (rope applied per-pass produces the
        --     same K@RoPE for matched positions) does not
        --     translate to numerical agreement at the merge
        --     boundary. Cache types that want overlay support
        --     therefore standardise on post-RoPE storage; pre-
        --     RoPE-store cache types remain on single-pass FA.
        -- The behavioural property: overlay-served attention is
        -- numerically equivalent to main-cache-served attention
        -- for the same set of attended positions, modulo the
        -- main cache's quantisation error.
}

-- Companion to ReadKVRecentFromOverlay: attended positions older
-- than the residual window are served from the quantised main
-- cache (Pass A in the two-pass dispatch).
rule ReadKVTailFromMainCache {
    when: ReadKVForAttention(query_position, attended_position, stream, seq_len)

    requires: attended_position <= seq_len - config.residual_window

    ensures: AttentionKeySource(
        query_position: query_position,
        attended_position: attended_position,
        source: main_cache
    )

    @guidance
        -- Implementation: Pass A's mask in the two-pass dispatch
        -- excludes cells with pos > seq_len - residual_window via
        -- a stream-wide boundary cut applied after the base
        -- causal mask (set_input_kq_mask_pass_a). When
        -- residual_window = 0, ReadKVRecentFromOverlay's
        -- requires fails for every position and this rule covers
        -- the whole sequence — single-pass FA on the main cache.
}

-- ============================================================
-- Invariants
-- ============================================================

-- The residual window must fit in the context and be
-- non-negative. Zero disables the overlay.
invariant ResidualWindowWithinContext {
    for c in Contexts:
        config.residual_window >= 0 and config.residual_window <= c.n_ctx
}

-- The overlay dtype must be a concrete float type at runtime.
-- The "auto" CLI sentinel must be resolved (by
-- ResolveOverlayDtypeAuto) before this invariant is checked.
invariant OverlayDtypeIsFloat {
    config.overlay_dtype in {f16, bf16}
}

-- SWA composition: when a sliding-window-attention layer is
-- stacked with a non-SWA base cache in a hybrid memory, the
-- overlay is meaningful only on the non-SWA side. The SWA
-- side runs with residual_window = 0 for its own cache. This
-- is enforced at cache construction; the hybrid-memory spec
-- owns the per-layer SWA flagging. Listed here as a scope
-- note rather than an expression-bearing invariant because
-- per-layer SWA typing lives outside this spec.

-- ============================================================
-- Actor Declarations
-- ============================================================

-- The overlay inspector is a test-boundary actor used to peek
-- at raw overlay bytes to verify write correctness. No
-- production caller takes this role.
actor OverlayInspector {
    identified_by: Context where n_layer > 0
}

-- ============================================================
-- Surfaces
-- ============================================================

-- Introspection API for verifying overlay writes. Exposes the
-- raw overlay bytes at a specific (layer, stream, slot) and
-- the byte size of one slot so callers can allocate a
-- receiving buffer. Writes are visible through this surface
-- after AppendOverlayRow fires.
surface OverlayPeek {
    facing inspector: OverlayInspector

    context ctx: Context

    exposes:
        ctx.n_layer
        ctx.n_stream

    provides:
        PeekOverlaySlot(inspector, ctx, layer, stream, slot)
        QueryOverlaySlotByteSize(inspector, ctx, layer)

    @guarantee WritesObservableAfterAppend
        -- After AppendOverlayRow has committed a write for a
        -- given (layer, stream, position), PeekOverlaySlot at
        -- the resolved slot returns those bytes until the
        -- next write wraps into the same slot.

    @guarantee SlotByteSizeMatchesDtype
        -- QueryOverlaySlotByteSize returns n_embd_k_gqa
        -- multiplied by the per-element byte size of
        -- config.overlay_dtype (2 bytes for f16 and bf16).
}

-- ============================================================
-- Open Questions
-- ============================================================

open question "Residual window size tuning: [TONBI-V3] defaults to 128 and reports it as the knee of the quality curve at model scales around 3B. Larger models or head_dim=256 configurations (Qwen3.5 9B) may need a larger window; smaller models may tolerate less. No public measurement campaign at our target sizes."

open question "Sliding vs fixed-start window: [TONBI-V3] implements the rolling-tail semantics (most recent N tokens overlaid in fp16). An alternative would be a fixed initial-tokens window (first N tokens in fp16 for the attention-sink / first-few-tokens phenomenon literature). This spec models the rolling-tail variant only."

open question "Interaction with quant.cpp Variant F multi-block split: the core spec (turbo-kv-4b.allium) inherits the per-128-element sub-block split. The residual window acts at the token level (rows); it is orthogonal to the within-row quantisation granularity. Composition should be clean, but the interaction has not been empirically tested."

open question "Auto-resolution placement: ResolveOverlayDtypeAuto is modelled as a rule because config defaults in Allium support only arithmetic over references and literals, and the auto-resolve logic inspects model weight types. A cleaner framing might be a dedicated config-default expression form, or a separate resolution phase. Left as a rule for now."

open question "Read-path structure: should attention over a recent-overlay plus quantised-tail cache use two-pass FA with LSE merge (one pass per source, merged softmax denominators), or single-pass with an assembled-K tensor spliced at query time? Merge granularity and cross-backend portability are at stake. Not yet prototyped."

open question "Reconciliation strategy selection — partially resolved per-operation. Removal: strategy (A) restore-from-main is selected (small affected set on the typical MTP rejection caller, k≤8; preserves overlay quality post-rewind). Shift / Divide / Copy / Keep: the strategy choice is deferred. Until decided, the implementation must guard those operations behind a hard error when residual_window > 0 and the operation reaches the recent window — so the gap fails loudly rather than silently corrupting attention. Lifting the guard requires either selecting a strategy per operation or generalising restore-from-main to non-removal mutations (Shift/Divide need a slot-move; Copy needs a cross-stream overlay copy; Keep is best served by full rebuild of dropped streams)."

open question "Persistence across session save/load: should the overlay participate in state_write / state_read on llama_memory_i? The in-memory ring buffer is lost across session-resume and server checkpoints today. Implications for long-running server deployments and multi-turn evaluation harnesses."

open question "Cross-backend equivalence: does the overlay require its own rule in turbo_kv_4b_backend.allium, or is it covered by that spec's general 'all backends produce the same output given the same inputs' invariant? Does the two-pass FA read path need its own cross-backend validation once it exists?"
